&= \frac{\sin40^{\circ}}{1 - \cos40^{\circ}}.
\end{align*}
Using the half-angle identity $\tan(\theta/2) = \frac{1 - \cos\theta}{\sin\theta}$, we can rewrite the expression as:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\sin40^{\circ}}{1 - \cos40^{\circ}} &= \frac{1}{\tan(40^{\circ}/2)} \\
&= \frac{1}{\tan20^{\circ}} \\
